<h4><strong>AUTHOR Queries</strong> </h4>
<div class="alert alert-danger" role="alert"><strong>NOTE: it is critical that you do not tell authors that we are conducting a trial because this may change their behaviour and responses.</strong></div>

<h5><strong>1. How do I complete the ARRIVE checklist? Is it ok to just add the page number, sections, or do I have to copy the actual text? </strong></h5>
<p>All approaches are fine, please note that upon revision the page numbers may change, so it may be advisable to copy paste the unique text that has been added.</p>

<h5><strong>2. I can’t modify the pdf for the ARRIVE checklist, how do I add this information to the right hand column? </strong></h5>
<p>You can save the pdf file as a word file, and add the changes to the word document. You can either submit the word file, or re-save the word document as a pdf.  </p>

<h5><strong>3. My colleague who submitted a manuscript a few months ago was not asked to provide an ARRIVE checklist, is this a change in policy?  </strong></h5>
<p>As indicated in <a href="http://www.plosone.org/static/editorial#animal">http://www.plosone.org/static/editorial#animal </a>PLOS ONE asks that authors follow the ARRIVE guidelines for all submission describing laboratory based animal research. As part of our internal technical checks we may request this at our own discretion.  </p>
<h5><strong>4. Is it mandatory to upload a completed ARRIVE checklist in order for my manuscript to proceed to peer review? Can I add it later at revision?  </strong></h5>
<p>It is not mandatory to upload a completed ARRIVE checklist at this point. However for reproducibility purposes we would prefer that you follow the ARRIVE guidelines and upload the completed ARRIVE checklist before peer review, as this may aid in the assessment of the work. For more information please see <a href="http://www.plosone.org/static/editorial#animal">http://www.plosone.org/static/editorial#animal </a></p>
